paragraphs.text:
%md
### One cow milk production
Colored areas represent Milk1, Milk2, Milk3, and DailyMilk. Areas stack one onto another, where the width of the area is proportional to milk production. 
At some dates Milk[1,2,3] are set to zero -- maybe that cow was not scanned before it was milked. That causes a random drops in the milk production. 

Ryne said that if all three milkings are zero it is likely that cow was not milked that day. If one or two milkings are zero it is likely that it was skipped.

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### Replace zeros with average production if one or two milkings are set to zero
At some days cow has unusually low milk production - because one or two or three milkings are set to zero.

Following plot shows the number of cows that produced less than 30 lbs per day -- spikes indicate possible software/hardware issues in themilking process.

We will replace zero values with average production.

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Replace milkings with 0 lbs with daily average
Next paragraph replaces zero values in Milk1, Milk2, Milk3 with daily farm average, but only for rows that have at least one milking different from 0. Rows with all three milkings set to zero are not averaged.

msg.data:
Replace milkings with 0 lbs with daily average

Next paragraph replaces zero values in Milk1, Milk2, Milk3 with daily farm average, but only for rows that have at least one milking different from 0. Rows with all three milkings set to zero are not averaged.

paragraphs.text:
dailyMilk76004Df = dailyMilk76004Df
    .withColumn("DailyMilkAvgPerMilking", $"DailyMilk" / $"MilkingsCountPerCow")
    .select("Date", "DailyMilkAvgPerMilking")
    .groupBy("Date")
    .agg(F.avg("DailyMilkAvgPerMilking").as("DailyMilkAvg"))
    .join(dailyMilk76004Df, Seq("Date"))

// only rows that have milk column value set to 0 are set to average value and returned
val replaceZeroMilkColWithAvg = (df: DataFrame, milkCol: Column, avgCol: Column) => df
    .filter(milkCol === 0)
    .drop(milkCol)
    .withColumnRenamed(avgCol.toString, milkCol.toString)
    
// fill milkings for cows that have at least one milking that day    
val averagedZeroMilk1Rows = replaceZeroMilkColWithAvg(dailyMilk76004Df.filter(F.col("MilkingsCountPerCow") > 0), $"Milk1", $"DailyMilkAvg").select("Date", "UniqueIdentifier", "Milk1")
val averagedZeroMilk2Rows = replaceZeroMilkColWithAvg(dailyMilk76004Df.filter(F.col("MilkingsCountPerCow") > 0), $"Milk2", $"DailyMilkAvg").select("Date", "UniqueIdentifier", "Milk2")
val averagedZeroMilk3Rows = replaceZeroMilkColWithAvg(dailyMilk76004Df.filter(F.col("MilkingsCountPerCow") > 0), $"Milk3", $"DailyMilkAvg").select("Date", "UniqueIdentifier", "Milk3")


val milk1Averaged = averagedZeroMilk1Rows.join(dailyMilk76004Df.withColumnRenamed("Milk1", "M1"), Seq("UniqueIdentifier", "Date"), "right").na.fill(0).withColumn("Milk1", $"M1" + $"Milk1").select("Date", "UniqueIdentifier", "Milk1")
val milk2Averaged = averagedZeroMilk2Rows.join(dailyMilk76004Df.withColumnRenamed("Milk2", "M2"), Seq("UniqueIdentifier", "Date"), "right").na.fill(0).withColumn("Milk2", $"M2" + $"Milk2").select("Date", "UniqueIdentifier", "Milk2")
val milk3Averaged = averagedZeroMilk3Rows.join(dailyMilk76004Df.withColumnRenamed("Milk3", "M3"), Seq("UniqueIdentifier", "Date"), "right").na.fill(0).withColumn("Milk3", $"M3" + $"Milk3").select("Date", "UniqueIdentifier", "Milk3")

val dailyMilk76004AveragedDf = dailyMilk76004Df.drop("Milk1", "Milk2", "Milk3", "DailyMilk")
    .join(milk1Averaged, Seq("Date", "UniqueIdentifier"), "left")
    .join(milk2Averaged, Seq("Date", "UniqueIdentifier"), "left")
    .join(milk3Averaged, Seq("Date", "UniqueIdentifier"), "left")
    .withColumn("DailyMilk", $"Milk1"+ $"Milk2" + $"Milk3" )

##### Dry start & end date calculated from events 
START
- user defined events contain DRY events
- in lactation data DDAT column represents dry start date, but ONLY for current pregnancy (redundant to user defined events)

    1) after calving/abortion
    2) when sold/died/moved - not longer on the farm
    3) more?
- Fresh - calving date
- User defined - Sold/Died/Move
- Profile data - ARDAT

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Bred events
Date - CONCEPTION date for a breeding event
Result - CURRENT state, this column is "mutable" 
    - P - while cow is pregnant
    - A - if abortion happens
    - O - if conception fails 
    - it is null after breeding when there is no information about current state
    - E - estimated breeding - probably irrelevant for milk production predictions - https://www.farmersweekly.co.za/farm-basics/how-to-livestock/understanding-estimated-breeding-values/
    - C - post conception breeding ??? - probably irrelevant for milk production predictions
    
    null --> O
         --> P --abortion--> A

var mddDailyMilk23751Df = spark.read.option("inferSchema", true).option("header", true).csv("/home/deegloo_ml/Development/Dario/data/MDD/23751/daily_milk.csv")
mddDailyMilk23751Df.sort("DATE").show(5, false)

// Set column namesto capitalized case
mddDailyMilk23751Df = mddDailyMilk23751Df.toDF(mddDailyMilk23751Df.columns.map(_.toLowerCase).map(_.capitalize): _*)
mddDailyMilk23751Df.show(5, false)

val transformDateUdf = F.udf(
    (date: String) => {
    val splits = date.split(" ")
    val dateStr = splits(5) + "-" + splits(1) + "-" + splits(2)
    val dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat("yyyy-MMM-dd") 
    val cal = Calendar.getInstance();
    cal.setTime(dateFormat.parse(dateStr))
    new Date(cal.getTimeInMillis())
})

// Transform date from string to DateType
mddDailyMilk23751Df = mddDailyMilk23751Df
    .withColumn("Date", transformDateUdf(mddDailyMilk23751Df.col("Date")))
    .withColumn("DailyMilk", $"Milk1" + $"Milk2" + $"Milk3")
    .withColumn("DailyMilkPerCow", $"Milkpercow1" + $"Milkpercow2" + $"Milkpercow3")
mddDailyMilk23751Df.show(5, false)
mddDailyMilk23751Df.printSchema()
